## **Detailed Statistical Analysis**

### **Descriptive Statistics: A Tale of Two Speeches**
The descriptive statistics reveal the profound character differences between the two artifacts. The high standard deviation in most dimensions indicates that the speakers occupy opposite ends of the character spectrum. Notably, the **Justice** dimension showed zero variance, with both speakers scoring identically (0.70), suggesting a shared emphasis on fairness, albeit likely defined in different terms [1]. Conversely, the minimal presence of **Fear** (Mean: 0.125) across both speeches is confirmed by a lack of supporting evidence [4].

| Dimension | Mean | Std Dev | Min | Max | Interpretation |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Dignity** | 0.625 | **0.318** | 0.40 | 0.85 | ‚≠ê High Variance: Key Differentiator |
| **Tribalism** | 0.400 | **0.283** | 0.20 | 0.60 | ‚≠ê High Variance: Key Differentiator |
| **Hope** | 0.650 | 0.212 | 0.50 | 0.80 | High Variance |
| **Resentment** | 0.325 | 0.247 | 0.15 | 0.50 | High Variance |
| **Justice** | 0.700 | **0.000** | 0.70 | 0.70 | ‚ùå No Variance: Common Ground |
| **Fear** | 0.125 | 0.106 | 0.05 | 0.20 | Low Presence Overall |
| **MC-SCI** | 0.060 | 0.017 | 0.048 | 0.073 | Clear differentiation in coherence |

### **Distribution of Moral Character Strategic Contradiction Index (MC-SCI)**
The MC-SCI scores show a clear separation, with McCain's concession speech demonstrating higher character coherence (less internal contradiction) than Sanders' populist address.

McCain (Institutional) ‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñí‚ñë‚ñë‚ñë‚ñë‚ñë‚ñë‚ñë‚ñë‚ñë‚ñë‚ñë 0.048  
